# Rust Doesn't Have a Garbage Collector

This is actually a common misconception worth clarifying directly. **Rust has no garbage collector** — this is one of its defining features.

---

## How Rust Manages Memory

Rust uses a system of compile-time rules that make a GC unnecessary.

### 1. Ownership
Every value has exactly one owner. When the owner goes out of scope, the value is freed **deterministically**.

```rust
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello"); // s owns the string
    // do stuff with s
} // s goes out of scope here — memory freed IMMEDIATELY, no GC needed
```

### 2. Borrowing & Lifetimes
You can reference data without taking ownership. The compiler verifies references never outlive the data they point to.

```rust
fn print_length(s: &String) { // borrowed, not owned
    println!("{}", s.len());
} // s is NOT freed here — the caller still owns it

fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    print_length(&s);       // borrow s
    println!("{}", s);      // s still valid here
} // s freed here
```

### 3. The Borrow Checker
The compiler enforces these rules **at compile time** — zero runtime overhead.

```rust
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    let r1 = &s;
    let r2 = &s;        // ✅ multiple immutable borrows OK
    // let r3 = &mut s; // ❌ compile error — can't mix mutable/immutable
    println!("{} {}", r1, r2);
}
```

